a ticket to a michael dukakis rally 
is easier to come by than one for a boston red sox home game or a 
performance of les miserables and a lot cheaper too 
what makes a dukakis ticket unusual is that people need one at 
all 
in fact they do if they want to be right down front within 
cheering distance of the democratic presidential candidate 
or in this campaign it might be more appropriate to say within 
heckling distance of the candidate 
immediately after labor day dukakis began encountering intense 
heckling particularly from antiabortion activists 
he had to fight to be heard during an appearance in early 
september in niles ill 
the campaign decided something had to be done their response 
was to rope off the area closest to the podium and require tickets 
for admission 
even students at rutgers university needed tickets to get close 
to dukakis when he delivered a speech on the environment 
in that case a ticket got a little star quality because actor 
robert redford introduced the candidate 
tickets also were required for rallies in melrose park ill 
jersey city nj and greensburg pa 
the tickets were free obtained from elected and party officials 
or from unions 
so at each rally the people down front were reliably 
enthusiastic for the candidate and cheered at every jibe against 
republican george bush their response usually drowning out the 
chants of bush supporters relegated to the fringes of the crowd 
another tool used to control hecklers is loud speakers the huge 
kind usually found at events like rock concerts 
a bank of megadecibel speakers placed at the rear of the crowd 
assures that the candidates voice will be heard above the chants 
of any hecklers 
at rutgers someone neglected to provide quite enough speakers 
and dukakis had to contend with a large group of probush students 
who chanted borrrring borrrring and recited the pledge of 
allegiance to the flag 
but they didnt have tickets so they were too far from the 
podium to effectively disrupt his speech 
