<TEXT>
the supreme court setting the stage for an 
important antitrust ruling today agreed to decide whether states 
may sue in behalf of those indirectly affected by illegal 
pricefixing 
the court voted to hear an appeal by four states california 
minnesota alabama and arizona seeking to participate in a 
multimilliondollar settlement of a nationwide conspiracy to fix 
cement prices 
justices john paul stevens and sandra day oconnor disqualified 
themselves from the case without explaining why 
lower courts had dismissed the states efforts to sue for county 
and municipal governments that had purchased cement or products 
containing cement the states sought the tripledamages awards 
allowed under federal antitrust law 
in throwing out the states lawsuits a federal trial judge and 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals relied on a 1977 supreme 
court decision in it the justices said federal antitrust law does 
not permit indirect purchasers to sue 
under the 1977 ruling if a manufacturer illegally conspires to 
fix a products price and sells it to a retailer the retailer may 
sue for triple damages but if the retailer passes on the illegally 
inflated price when selling the product to the ultimate consumer 
the consumer may not use federal antitrust law to sue 
lawyers for the four states supported by the reagan 
administration say congress never intended federal antitrust law 
to negate state laws protecting indirect purchasers 
a spate of lawsuits were filed against cement manufacturers in 
1976 and 1977 alleging a nationwide conspiracy to fix prices each 
of the four states involved in todays court action filed a suit 
based in part on state laws protecting indirect purchasers 
state laws in california minnesota and alabama expressly give 
indirect purchasers the right to sue 
arizonas law could be interpreted to permit such suits 
the litigation was consolidated in federal court in arizona and 
by 1981 cement manufacturers had agreed to pay 32 million to 
settle the case 
direct purchasers then challenged the states right to be 
compensated for indirect purchases 
us district judge manuel l real dismissed the indirect 
purchasers claims in 1985 and the 9th circuit court upheld his 
dismissal last year 
reagan administration lawyers in supporting the ensuing supreme 
court appeal by the four states said two key federal antitrust 
laws contain no statement of congressional intent to preempt 
state antitrust remedies 
in these circumstances the administration lawyers argued 
there is no basis for a conclusion that federal antitrust law 
preempts state indirectpurchaser statutes 
they said at least 11 other states and the district of columbia 
have enacted laws expressly giving indirect purchasers the right to 
sue 
the states are colorado hawaii illinois kansas maryland 
michigan mississippi new mexico rhode island south dakota and 
wisconsin 
the case is california vs arc america corp 871862 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

