<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether communities may seek to protect young teenagers by barring 
anyone over 18 from dance halls or other establishments catering to 
minors 
the court said it will consider reinstating a dallas ordinance 
that licensed certain dance halls on the condition only teens 14 to 
18 and their parents or guardians be admitted as patrons 
a texas appeals court struck down the ordinance ruling that it 
unduly interferes with young peoples constitutionally protected 
right to associate with whom they please 
in urging the justices to reinstate the ordinance dallas 
officials said the potential harm comes from the association 
with persons who may influence the behavior of the children not 
only at the dance hall where supervision exists but also away from 
the dance hall 
but the state appeals court last oct 29 ruled that the age 
limit cannot be enforced 
a childs right of association may not be abridged simply on 
the premise that he might associate with those who would persuade 
him into bad habits such as illegal use of drugs or alcohol the 
state court said 
it added it is primarily the responsibility of the parent 
not the city to tell the minor how old his dance partner may be 
the answer lies in supervision not in strict segregation by age 
group 
there is no showing that the less restrictive means of 
supervision will be ineffectual to control the evil perceived in 
allowing say a 20yearold to enter the premises and peacably and 
consensually dance with a 14yearold the state court said 
the ordinance had been challenged by charles m stanglin who 
operates the twilight skating rink in dallas 
stanglin has a socalled class e dance hall license issued 
to those dance places catering to minors 
he divided the floor of his skating rink so that patrons dance 
or skate to the same music in full view of one another no alcohol 
is allowed inside 
the ordinance he challenged forbids anyone not between the ages 
of 14 and 18 except for parents or legal guardians of patrons to 
dance or even be on the premises 
the state court struck down the agesegregation portion of the 
dallas ordinance but upheld that portion imposing midnight curfew 
for such establishments 
the case is dallas vs stanglin 871848 
</TEXT>
