the supreme court today left intact a ruling 
that states must compensate tree nursery owners required to destroy 
healthy citrus plants that may have been exposed to an infectious 
disease 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by florida 
officials who say the ruling could force the state to pay 250 
million to nursery owners 
the florida supreme court ruled in january that the state must 
pay two nurseries for destruction of their trees 
the state court ordered a trial to determine how much money is 
owed midflorida growers inc and himrod amp himrod citrus nursery 
both based in hardee county 
during two weeks in 1984 the state agriculture department 
burned 137880 of midfloridas trees and budwood and 143594 of 
himrods 
state officials said they were worried the plants were infected 
with citrus canker that could spread if the trees were sold to 
citrus growers 
the nursery owners said the treeeradication program was less a 
means of preventing public harm than a way of maintaining public 
confidence in the state citrus industry 
the state supreme court agreed that destruction of healthy 
trees benefited the entire citrus industry and in turn floridas 
economy thereby conferring a public benefit rather than preventing 
a public harm 
the state court also said there is a distinction when officials 
destroy decayed fruit unwholesome meat or diseased cattle in 
those cases the property is worthless the state court said 
there was ample evidence the destroyed trees were healthy the 
state court said adding that 50000 citrus plants from the two 
nurseries were sold to customers and no canker ever was discovered 
on the buyers premises 
the state court said the nursery owners are entitled to just 
compensation as required by the constitutions fifth amendment when 
officials seize private property 
florida officials said they could end up being forced to pay 
250 million to all nursery owners in the state whose trees were 
destroyed to prevent the canker disease from spreading 
the states appeal was supported by florida citrus growers and 
officials from nine other states who said the nursery owners are 
not entitled to compensation 
the states are idaho louisiana mississippi oklahoma south 
dakota tennessee vermont virginia and wyoming 
the case is department of agriculture vs midflorida growers 
872123 
