the supreme court in a case of widespread 
interest among educators today agreed to decide whether new york 
state universities may ban some commercial activities in dormitory 
rooms 
the court said it will review a ruling that students rights 
were ignored when college officials barred a pennsylvania cookware 
company from conducting its sales pitch in dormitories 
an appeal by the state university of new york suny to revive 
the ban on its various campuses received support from university 
officials in 10 states and groups representing thousands of college 
administrations nationwide 
the suny board of trustees adopted a rule in 1966 to prohibit 
most commercial enterprises from operating on state university 
campuses 
the ban was challenged by american future systems inc a 
housewares company in bryn mawr pa after one of its 
representatives was arrested in 1982 at the state university campus 
in cortland ny 
she had refused to leave a dormitory 
afs attracts customers by offering free florida vacations to 
students who arrange sales demonstrations in their dormitory rooms 
for groups of their friends 
us district judge neal p mccurn upheld the suny ban against 
such activities ruling that afs had no freespeech right to sell 
its products on campus 
but the focus of the case shifted on appeal the company 
withdrew as a plaintiff from the case and its lawyers now represent 
suny students who are challenging the prohibition 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals last march noted the 
change as it overturned mccurns ruling 
the case no longer involves an effort by outsiders to gain 
access to university property the appeals court said rather 
it concerns only the constitutional rights of students in their 
dormitories 
the appeals court added the suny regulation survived 
constitutional scrutiny by judge mccurn only because the first 
amendment rights of students were ignored 
without spelling out the details the appeals court sent the 
case back to the judge with instructions to draw a suitable 
order that will not offend students rights to receive 
information and hear speech in their dormitory rooms 
the appeals court suggested the university find a less 
restrictive means of meeting its legitimate interest in preventing 
disruption and overcommercialization on campuses 
in a friendofthecourt legal brief officials from 
universities in 10 states said the appeals court ruling will 
seriously erode their power to control campus life 
this case implicates far more than the sale of cookware by a 
pennsylvania pots and pans purveyor the officials said the 
fundamental right of state colleges and universities to control the 
use of their premises is at issue 
the officials are from state universities in california 
connecticut florida michigan illinois ohio south carolina 
rhode island new jersey and vermont 
other groups supporting the suny appeal are the american council 
on education the american association of state colleges and 
universities the national association of state universities and 
land grant colleges and the national association of student 
personnel administrators 
the case is state university of new york vs fox 872013 
