the supreme court today rejected appeals by 
investors who lost money in the largest municipal bond default in 
us history stemming from a doomed nuclear power project in 
washington state 
the court citing the lack of a substantial federal 
question let stand a ruling that dismissed some key investor 
claims triggered by the 225 billion default 
the justices also rejected an appeal by the bond counsel in the 
case seeking additional legal protection 
investors ranging from individuals to major corporations sued 
the washington public power supply system and numerous others in 
1984 
the washington state supreme court last year upheld a state law 
that retroactively expanded protection for cities and utilities 
against some bondholder claims 
that ruling made it more difficult for investors to recover 
their losses by suing public agencies but at the same time the 
state court permitted other investor claims to proceed to trial 
a trial began last month in tucson ariz in which more than 
24000 bond buyers are charging fraud by 19 defendants 16 
utilities two engineering firms and a financial adviser the 
defendants allegedly withheld crucial information from investors 
who bought bonds to finance construction of two nuclear power 
plants 
the appeal acted on today challenged portions of the 1987 
washington supreme court decision upholding state law protections 
for cities and utilities the law is aimed at shielding the public 
agencies and ultimately their electricity customers from being 
sued for alleged negligence 
the law does not protect the agencies from being sued for fraud 
and those allegations are being aired in the tucson trial 
the state court said protecting the agencies from being sued for 
negligence does not interfere unlawfully with interstate commerce 
does not violate investors due process rights and does not 
illegally impair any contractual agreement between bondholders and 
issuers of the securities 
the nations highest court in 1985 rejected an earlier bid by 
investors to ease recovery of their losses 
all told investors say they have lost 7 billion the 225 
billion in bonds plus interest they would have received if there 
had been no default 
the bonds were to finance two proposed wppss nuclear plants to 
meet an anticipated increase in power needs in the northwest but 
facilities already built by the mid1970s proved adequate to supply 
the region and construction of the two new plants was abandoned in 
1982 that triggered the bond default 
eightyeight cities utilities and electrical cooperatives in 
the northwest took part in agreements to build the two plants 
in a companion case acted on today the bond counsel firm of 
wood dawson smith amp hellman appealed for greater protection from 
being sued the firm said it should be given the same protection 
afforded the public agencies that issued the bonds 
the cases acted on today are american express vs wppss 
871889 haberman vs wppss 871897 and wood dawson vs haberman 
872109 
