<TEXT>
the supreme court today turned away an appeal 
accusing defeated high court nominee robert h bork of improperly 
participating in a case just before he quit as a federal judge 
the court without comment rejected arguments that borks 
failure to disqualify himself from a libel case violated the 
conservative liberty lobby groups dueprocess rights 
liberty lobby sued the wall street journal for 50 million over 
a 1984 article and a 1985 column that appeared in the newspaper 
the column was written by suzanne garment a journal writer 
whose husband leonard garment is a longtime friend of borks 
garment a washington lawyer served as borks chief spokesman 
during an unsuccessful campaign to win senate confirmation of 
borks nomination to the supreme court 
the senate rejected bork by a 5842 vote last october 
borks participation in the liberty lobby case was challenged 
because of his relationship with the garments 
in both the article and column liberty lobby was referred to as 
antisemitic and was linked to books authored by an advocate of 
racial betterment through genetic selection 
although liberty lobby admits to being an antizionist 
organization it denies being antisemitic the lawsuit also denied 
any links with the authors works 
us district judge thomas penfield jackson whose participation 
in the case also was challenged dismissed the lawsuit in 1986 
a threejudge panel of the us circuit court of appeals here 
upheld the libel suits dismissal last feb 5 in an opinion 
written by bork 
bork quit the federal bench that same day 
in his opinion for the appellate panel bork said we tend to 
agree with the district court that if the term antisemitic has a 
core factual meaning then the truth of the description was proved 
here 
the appeals court also rejected liberty lobbys denial of a link 
to the mentioned books published by noontide press in torrance 
calif 
the record evidence that both group treasurer willis carto 
and liberty lobby exercise substantial financial and editorial 
control over the publishing activities of noontide is in our view 
compelling bork wrote 
the full court of appeals last feb 25 denied liberty lobbys 
request to have its lawsuit revived and bork disqualified 
the case is liberty lobby vs dow jones amp co 872053 
</TEXT>
