<DOCNO> AP881003-0137 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether those who win partial victories in civil rights lawsuits 
losing on the central issue are entitled to recover their 
attorneys fees 
the court said it will hear an appeal by school teachers in 
texas who challenged antiunion regulations 
the regulations adopted by the garland independent school 
district barred teacher union representatives from visiting 
schools during regular school hours or using school public address 
systems or other communications facilities 
the rules also prohibited private conversations among teachers 
regarding the employee organizations and also barred any teacher 
from using a schools internal mail system or bulletin board to 
discuss union activities 
the 5th us circuit court of appeals upheld the regulations 
affecting union representatives but the appeals court said it 
violates the freespeech and freeassociation rights of teachers to 
ban private conversations or prevent them from using the mail or 
bulletin board facilities 
the appeals court ruled in february that the texas state 
teachers association and the garland education association which 
filed the suit are not entitled to be reimbursed for attorneys 
fees 
federal civil rights laws provide that the prevailing party 
in such cases is entitled to reimbursement the idea is to provide 
an incentive for lawyers to represent civil rights plaintiffs who 
frequently have limited financial resources and find it difficult 
to get legal representation 
at issue in the case acted on today is what constitutes a 
prevailing party 
the 5th circuit court said the teacher unions did not succeed 
on the central issue of their suit and did not obtain the primary 
relief sought the main thrust of this lawsuit was their attempt 
to open up garland independent school district campuses during 
school hours to outside representatives of employee organizations 
they failed in this attempt 
the appeals court acknowledged that the teachers prevailed on 
significant secondary issues 
in appealing to the supreme court the teacher groups said there 
is confusion among federal appeals courts over the prevailing 
party issue and they asked the justices to provide clear 
guidelines 
the case is texas state teachers association vs garland 
independent school district 871759 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

