<TEXT>
the supreme court today rejected a challenge 
to the rates being charged for transporting oil through the 
transalaska pipeline 
the justices without comment left intact a rate agreement 
between alaska and the pipelines eight owners 
the rates were challenged by the arctic slope regional corp 
established under alaska law to protect the rights of inupiat 
eskimos 
lawyers for arctic said the pipeline rate agreement which 
extends through the year 2011 will have a critical effect on the 
development and cost of oil from the alaska north slope an energy 
resource vital to our nations economy and security 
after large reserves of oil were discovered on alaskas north 
slope in 1969 eight oil companies constructed an 800mile pipeline 
to the allweather port of valdez on the states pacific coast 
the pipeline was completed in 1977 at a cost of some 9 billion 
the alaska law aimed at promoting oil production extinguished 
the land claims of native alaskans by compensating them with money 
arctic is one of 13 regional corporations given ownership of 
lands formerly held by natives arctic leases much of its 45 
million acres for the benefit of its inupiat eskimo shareholders 
oil from arctics lands likely will start being shipped through 
the pipeline sometime in the 1990s and the oils value to arctic 
will be reduced dollarfordollar by charges levied for 
transporting it 
after nine years of administrative proceedings alaska and the 
pipelines eight owners reached a rate agreement in 1986 
arctic attempted to challenge the agreement contending that the 
perbarrel rates it yielded are too high 
but the federal energy regulatory commission approved the 
agreement as uncontested after ruling that arctic was not 
particularly aggrieved by the pipeline rates 
a federal appeals court here upheld the commission ruling last 
oct 27 after noting that the rate agreement is not binding on 
arctic and that arctic is free to challenge the rates once oil 
from its lands begin to pass through the pipeline 
arctic can properly be left out in the cold for the moment 
the appeals court ruled adding the commission acted within its 
lawful authority and discretion in closing a long and wearisome 
chapter in the saga of transalaska pipeline rate regulation 
the pipelines owners are amerada hess arco bp exxon mobil 
phillips sohio and unocal 
the case is arctic slope regional corp vs ferc 871869 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

