<TEXT>
politicians sought agreement monday on a measure to 
limit secret voting in parliament in a bid to stave off a possible 
government crisis 
a vote is expected in the chamber of deputies later this week 
and political analysts said premier ciriaco de mitas 6monthold 
coalition government hangs in the balance 
since the vote itself will be secret politicians see the 
possibility of snipers those who vote against their own party 
as being a determining factor 
if the proposal is rejected there is no doubt mr de mita will 
resign said francesco donofrio a constitutional expert for de 
mitas christian democrat party 
italy is one of the few western democracies where most 
parliamentary votes are secret and rollcalls are taken only on 
votes of confidence the practice has been blamed in part for the 
chronic instability of italian governments 
de mitas predecessor fellow christian democrat giovanni goria 
resigned as head of italys 47th postwar government in march after 
losing a series of secret votes his seven months in office were 
plagued by political infighting 
the same five parties that had made up gorias government agreed 
in april to reform the coalition under de mita by placing limits on 
the secret ballot 
they agreed the secrecy would only be retained for questions 
involving fundamental liberties or for issues of conscience such as 
genetic manipulation or abortion but some members of parliament 
have had second thoughts viewing the secret vote as the only way 
to keep some degree of freedom from the tight party discipline 
foreign minister giulio andreotti a powerful christian 
democrat took some distance from de mita last week when he said 
parliament shouldnt exaggerate any changes and should consider 
limiting open voting to financial questions 
a series of amendments to limit open voting have been tacked on 
to the original coalition government proposal and the chamber of 
deputies will vote on these 
mario usellini a christian democrat said in a newspaper 
interview that about 10 percent of the 630 members of the chamber 
of deputies are inclined to break party discipline but would be 
afraid to do so if most votes were open 
they are deputies with a weak position in their party and feel 
most exposed because they fear expulsion from the party and an 
electoral boycott he told milans corriere della sera 
the secret vote also is believed to help special interests 
since no voting records can be kept 
