<TEXT>
analyses used by federal agencies to check on 
pesticides in the nations food supply cant detect about half the 
pesticides permitted to be used a research arm of congress 
reported monday 
food is checked by the food safety inspection service of the 
agriculture department which analyzes meat and poultry the 
departments agricultural marketing service which analyzes eggs 
and the food and drug administration part of the health and human 
services department which analyzes all other foods 
as a routine matter the agencies can use only multiresidue 
analyses methods that reveal the concentration of a number of 
compounds except in special cases methods useful for detecting 
only one compound are too expensive to use the congressional 
office of technology assessment reported 
there are 316 pesticide active ingredients for which the 
environmental protection agency has established maximum permissible 
concentration of residues in food or tolerances 
the ota report said the five multiresidue methods used by the 
food and drug administration can detect only 163 compounds 
similarly these methods can detect only 10 of 74 compounds with 
pending or temporary tolerances 25 of 56 with no established 
tolerance and 92 of 297 breakdown products impurities or other 
pesticideassociated chemicals 
the report presented less detail on the food safety inspection 
service but did say the four methods used there can detect about 
40 chemicals 
fsis has identified 10 highly ranked pesticides it would like 
to monitor routinely but cannot using its multiresidue methods 
the report said 
fda spokesman emil corwin said the agency had not had a chance 
to study the report and therefore could not comment a chemist to 
whom he referred detailed questions did not answer 
usda spokeswoman karen stuck said she was seeking comment from 
agency officials 
diane baxter staff scientist for the national coalition against 
the misuse of pesticides said the lack of coverage in routine 
monitoring worries us very much 
she said fungicides of a class called ebdc whose breakdown 
products cause cancer and the herbicide glyphosate are chemicals 
that need routine monitoring 
results from what analyses could be performed showed a low 
failure rate the report said 25 percent of about 12700 samples 
last year showed excessive residues but the sampling was not 
random 
samples contained a higher percentage of fruits and vegetables 
than the general food supply and were biased toward foodpesticide 
combinations known to yield residue problems 
