<DOCNO> AP881003-0215 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court announced monday it will 
settle a dispute over pension benefits in which billions of dollars 
could be at stake 
the court said it will hear an appeal by the mead corp of 
dayton ohio which was ordered to pay additional pension benefits 
to six workers at a virginia company formerly owned by mead 
mead acquired lynchburg foundry co in virginia in 1968 and set 
up a pension plan that provided earlyretirement benefits to 
workers at age 62 and had 30 years of service 
mead sold lynchburg foundry to a new owner in 1983 and 
terminated the pension plan 
it refused to pay the early retirement benefits to the six 
workers five of them had worked more than 30 years apiece although 
none had reached 62 the sixth had worked 28 years and was 61 
the six were given lumpsum benefits by mead that were based on 
a retirement age of 65 a total of about 56500 less for all six 
than they would have received under the earlyretirement plan 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals ruled in april 1987 that 
mead must pay additional benefits to the former employees from a 
10 million surplus in the companys pension fund 
the appeals court said five of the six workers must receive 
benefits based on what they would be entitled to if they retired at 
62 and the benefits for the sixth should be calculated on a 
retirement age of 63 that he would reach with 30 years service 
the appeals court based its ruling on the employee retirement 
income security act of 1974 a federal law designed to protect 
workers pensions 
mead said billions of dollars could be at stake in the case for 
pension plans nationwide 
more than 49 million workers are covered by 849000 retirement 
plans that control almost 2 trillion in assets the company said 
and the issues involved in the case acted on monday affect more 
than a quarter of those plans 
the case is mead corp vs tilley 871868 
</TEXT>
