<TEXT>
saudi arabia joined the nuclear 
nonproliferation treaty on monday in a move that the state 
department praised as a demonstration of that countrys peaceful 
intentions in the middle east 
saudi foreign minister prince saud alfaisal presented the 
documents certifying saudi adherence to the treaty at a ceremony 
attended by secretary of state george p shultz and united nations 
officials 
the united states is one of the countries authorized under the 
treaty to receive such documents 
us officials said saudi officials told shultz earlier this 
year of their intention to subscribe to the treaty under which 
signatory nations promise not to acquire a nuclear weapons 
capability among other requirements 
the reagan administration had been somewhat concerned about 
saudi arabias intentions after the monarchy acquired css2 missiles 
from china the chinese had never exported the weapon previously 
and had equipped its own arsenal with nuclear warheads according 
to us officials who asked not to be identified 
however saudi officials have assured the united states that the 
missiles they imported from china are not equipped with nuclear 
warheads 
israel has long been concerned about saudi arabias intentions 
because of the proximity of the two countries israel has not 
signed the treaty 
the united states is extremely pleased that saudi arabia has 
joined the community of nations embraced by the treaty state 
department spokesman charles redman said 
he called the accord the most widely supported arms control 
treaty in history 
the broad consensus among mankind that the spread of nuclear 
weapons is a danger that can and must be avoided redman said 
with its accession to the treaty today saudi arabia is 
strengthening the global nonproliferation regime demonstrating 
its peaceful intentions in the region 
redman expressed hope that all states which have not yet joined 
the treaty will decide to do so 
shultz spent the day conferring with highranking arab 
diplomats including iraqi foreign minister tariq aziz 
redman said both countries agreed on the importance of expanding 
relations after an extended period of acrimony generated by us 
allgeations that iraq used chemical weapons against kurdish rebels 
he said aziz repeated his sept 17 statement in which he 
promised to abide by commitments iraq has undertaken concerning 
chemical weapons the reagan administration has said it interprets 
that statement to mean iraq forswears the use of such weaponry 
