using charts and maps on easel boards the task force commander 
col eldridge casto jr and his aides explain their mission to 
build the final seven miles of a 34mile road into the yoro valley 
casto a spare man with a west virginia drawl speaks with pride 
of the men and women under his command who have moved thousands 
upon thousands of cubic yards of earth crushed ton upon ton of 
rock into gravel and forced a formidable path across towering 
mountains 
he speaks too of the hundreds of doctors and nurses of the 
national guard who have gone into dozens of remote villages to 
vaccinate and treat men women children cows horses goats 
sheep dogs and cats for an array of exotic ailments seldom seen in 
the united states 
it is invaluable experience the colonel tells his visitors 
it is something we simply cant get at home 
so for three years running thousands of national guard members 
have come to honduras in the novembertojune dry season to work 
for two weeks alongside regular us army and honduran soldiers on 
a project once known as blazing trails86 and now called 
fuertes caminos88 the spanish name means strong roads 
when work is completed in a few days casto says the yoro 
valley will for the first time be open to the outside world 
permitting access to new markets by its peasant farmers and 
creating the possibility of development in one of the poorest parts 
of one of the poorest nations in the western hemisphere 
the humanitarian aspects of this project are immeasurable 
the colonel tells his listeners who include a bank president from 
