<DOCNO> AP881003-0318 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to order the 
government to compensate the owner of a nuclear fuel reprocessing 
plant that was denied an operating license as a result of a carter 
administration decision on curbing international nuclear 
proliferation 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by the barnwell 
sc plants owner who says that a changed federal policy cost the 
facility more than 200 million 
the justices also turned down a related appeal by a company that 
signed a contract to transport nuclear fuel to and from barnwell 
a federal appeals court in washington calling the plant one 
of the most remarkable white elephants in the nations history 
ruled in february that plant owner alliedgeneral nuclear services 
is not entitled to compensation 
the plant was denied a license in 1977 when former president 
jimmy carter decided to defer indefinitely the recycling of 
plutonium for nuclear power 
the appeals court said the abandonment of reprocessing was 
intended to bolster the nations credibility in discouraging 
plutonium production abroad 
even though president reagan lifted the ban in 1981 there has 
been no move by the nuclear regulatory commission to license the 
barnwell facility 
most of it stands there empty and forlorn the appeals 
court said 
the appeals court rejected alliedgenerals claim that it should 
be compensated because government inducements prompted the company 
to build the plant 
the government provided the land for the facility and urged the 
company to build it the owners said they said denying the plant 
permission to operate in effect was the same as a government 
seizure of the property without constitutionally required just 
compensation 
but the appeals court said no one has a legally protected 
right to use property in a manner that is injurious to the safety 
of the general public 
there can be no doubt that president carter considered nuclear 
proliferation was a threat and that consequently the processing 
of spent fuel at the barnwell plant was a danger he must avert 
the appeals court said 
the appeals court also ruled against nl industries inc which 
said it invested more than 15 million in transportation systems 
for the barnwell facility 
nl industries signed a contract with alliedgeneral in 1971 to 
provide rail and truck service depots and other facilities to 
carry nuclear fuel to and from barnwell 
nl industries said the government ratified the contract and 
was intimately involved in the development of the 
transportation system 
the cases are alliedgeneral vs us 871902 and nl 
industries vs us 871922 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

