<TEXT>
the coowner of the worlds largest 
organic grape vineyard attributes his success and longevity to an 
unusual blend of philosophies he terms environmental capitalism 
thats really what it is its taking the good that goes on in 
the world and making a few dollars off of it and why not said 
steve pavich 39 who oversees the richgrove califbased pavich 
and sons vineyards 
the sheer size of the operation 1400 acres in california and 
arizona is unusual in organic farming circles most organic 
vineyards range from 40 to 200 acres said bob scrowcroft 
executive director of the california certified organic growers 
association 
most organic growers will say the paviches are 10 years ahead 
of everybody in growing techniques and marketing said joyce 
johnson director of the kern county valley action network an 
environmental group 
although pavich is dedicated to organic farming techniques he 
doesnt condemn other growers who use pesticides 
im not telling any other growers that they have to stop using 
pesticides i say if they need to do it to survive thats what 
they need to do he said 
organic farming is an agricultural practice that does not rely 
on the use of synthetic pesticides or fertilizers in california 
growers marketing their produce under the organic associations 
label are subject to strict guidelines on fertilization and pest 
control 
the guidelines are designed to separate the truly organic 
produce from other goods advertised as natural or 
pesticidefree 
pavich never uses herbicides or commercial fertilizers but has 
used what he calls biologically acceptable insecticides the 
pavich ranches havent sprayed at all during the past four years 
were at the top end of the transition now it took us from 
1971 to 1981 10 years to figure out all of the parameters we 
are working with today pavich said at that time we had about 
onetenth of the materials we have today and had to set up much of 
that myself 
information on organic farming techniques was hard to come by 
when pavich began farming 750 acres in 1971 
there is no place where you can have it handed to you on a 
silver platter pavich said 
but the subsequent years of research field testing and 
trialanderror was a long and hard process 
pavich reluctantly offered a few details about his techniques 
which he said took 17 years to perfect and would be in great demand 
in the highly competitive field 
most of it has to do with timing he said when you are in 
tune with that rhythm of what nature is doing then its much 
easier to deal with the problems 
at first pavich spent twice as much money on various organic 
fertilizing techniques than a conventional farm would spend on 
synthetic nitrogen fertilizers now he estimates his fertilizing 
costs are about the same as a vineyard using commercial fertilizers 
pavich and his brother tom 32 accomplished that by planting a 
wide variety of cover crops and using manure fertilizers and gypsum 
to keep the soil productive reduce erosion and hold down the costs 
of pest control 
yields on the pavich ranches are in line with industry averages 
production now totals 1 million boxes annually 
for example pavich says his vineyards in richgrove produce 
about 650 lugs of thompson seedless grapes per acre the california 
table grape commission says average thompson harvest is 600 lugs 
per acre with this years bumper crop however some growers are 
harvesting up to 900 lugs an acre said commission president bruce 
obbink 
a lug is a box containing about 23 pounds of grapes 
some pavich grapes can fetch a 10 to 15 percent premium because 
they are organic but the price usually is in line with the market 
like other organic growers pavich is frustrated by what he 
considers a dearth of research on sustainable farming techniques 
in contrast to the vigorous marketing by agricultural chemical 
companies 
but universities are warming up to sustainable agriculture 
research he feels 
ironically pavich and other organic table grape growers have 
been caught in the crossfire of the united farm workers boycott to 
protest use of five pesticides on table grapes 
the union has issued conflicting statements about how the 
boycott applies to organically grown produce 
like other grape growers pavich says the boycott hasnt 
affected sales but hes had to devote time to defending the 
integrity of his organic crop when ufw pickets demand removal of 
his grapes from stores across the country 
they put a question in a lot of peoples minds and we have to 
answer those he said 
scrowcroft said the recent surge of attention to the ufw boycott 
has ignored what organic activists consider a solution to the 
problem of worker pesticide poisonings and consumer anxiety over 
food safety organic growing 
nobody has identified the positive out there that positive is 
certified organic food he said 
</TEXT>
