a stockholders lawsuit against media 
general inc involving the companys twotiered stock structure was 
dismissed monday by a federal judge 
us district judge richard l williams agreed with arguments by 
attorneys for media general that the complaint of harvey jasper a 
new york lawyer who owns 100 shares of company stock did not have 
a strong enough legal basis to proceed to trial at one time 
jasper owned 5000 shares of media general 
williams also rejected an argument by jaspers attorneys that 
the complaint be considered a class action on behalf of other 
holders of media general class a common stock 
jaspers lawsuit contended that a 1987 media general proxy 
statement was misleading about whether the company would accept a 
buyout offer jasper bought stock after the proxy statement was 
issued 
the statement defined in some detail the relative strengths of 
the companys a and b common stock classes he contended he lost 
money on his investments because those who control the stock did 
not state the company never would be for sale 
james w tredway an attorney for media general argued that if 
the proxy statement lacked any clarity the problem was resolved in 
october 1987 when the company issued a statement after the purchase 
of a block of class a stock by hollywood producer burt sugarman 
the company said it could not imagine circumstances in which 
owners of the controlling stock in media general ever would sell 
their shares 
jaspers lawsuit was related to an unsuccessful takeover offer 
from sugarman on feb 29 sugarman proposed to buy all of media 
generals a and b stock for 6150 a share then raised the offer 
to 70 and also sought to have himself and two associates named to 
