a news release that continental had received the route through a 
procedural quirk that united had forged the route into a 
national asset and that competing japanese carriers would be 
elated by a divestiture that would weaken the competitive vigor of 
united 
that is precisely why such a result runs flatly contrary to 
the public interest the statement said 
the transportation department made its decision after the 
justice department refused to challenge a federal court decision in 
august ordering the route be given to continental 
transportation secretary jim burnley reportedly had argued in 
favor of appealing the case but the justice department refused to 
take further legal action 
the court decision favoring continental upheld on procedural 
grounds an administrative law judges original ruling in the 
controversy last year since that administrative judges ruling a 
succession of senior department officials have disagreed over who 
should get the route choosing united at one point and then 
american airlines 
united has flown the seattletokyo route since april 1983 
the seattletokyo route previously was flown by pan american 
world airways but united assumed the route temporarily when it 
purchased pan ams pacific division in 1986 
the transportation department approved uniteds acquisition of 
the pan am routes only under the condition that the seattletokyo 
route be dealt with separately 
stephen wolf uniteds chairman and president contends that the 
selection process was flawed 
the public deserves more from its government than to have a 
vital decision of national transportation policy with such 
important consequences hinge on a procedural accident he said 
